                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This is a huge pet peeve for me, and all that it entails. I am the enchanter - I call for the mob we kill and the mob we mez.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   You're fighting against the tide here.  Because across the entire game, I think you'll find that the main tank <span style="font-weight: bold">always</span> calls targets, not the Enchanter.  It's his job to select and engage a mob, and your job to adjust to his decisions, not the other way around.
<br />

<br />
   The main tank is the focal point of the attack.  Until they can engage, gain aggro and control the mob, most of your group is just sitting around twiddling their thumbs.  And while it is fairly trivial for a tank to learn which mobs are controllable by what means, it is nigh unto impossible for anyone else but the main tank to know precisely how under control the current fight actually is.
<br />

<br />
   I don't know why your tank switched targets.  Very likely it was the wrong decision at the time.  But the right player made the decision.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
